GARMEN XV.

This is probably a composition from the Greek, and I should think a pretty close imitation. It is addressed to an imaginary Neaera by the poet in his own person. He complains of her deserting him for a wealthier rival. Horace introduces the same name in a much later ode (iii. 14. 21), and it is used throughout the third book of Elegies commonly attributed to Tibullus. The ode is in Ovid’s style, and worthy to have been written by him. By the same argument that is applied to Epode xi. (see Introduction) Franke and Kirchner assign to this the date A.U.c. 721.
